            <div type="bibliography">
                <p><bibl><ptr target="reycoquais2002"/> <citedRange unit="entry">7</citedRange>, with a plate</bibl>, whence 
                    <bibl><ptr target="seg"/> <citedRange>52.1607</citedRange></bibl>, <bibl><ptr target="feisselBE"/>2003.580</bibl>, 
                    also <bibl><ptr target="feissel2006"/> <citedRange>683</citedRange></bibl>;
                    <bibl><ptr target="ityr2006"/> <citedRange>133</citedRange></bibl>.
                    </p>
            </div>
            
            <div type="edition" xml:lang="grc" xml:space="preserve">
               <ab>
                   <lb n="1"/><g ref="symbol.xml#crux"/> <w lemma="τόπος"><expan><abbr>Τ<hi rend="superscript">ό</hi></abbr><abbr>π<hi rend="superscript">ο</hi></abbr><ex>ϲ</ex></expan></w>  
                   <lb n="2"/> <orgName ref="#blue" nymRef="#παγανόι Βένετοι"><w lemma="παγανός"><expan><abbr>παγ</abbr><ex>ανῶν</ex></expan></w> <w lemma="βένετος">Βενέτων</w></orgName> 
                   </ab>
             </div> 
           
            <div type="apparatus"><listApp><app loc="2"><rdg resp="#reycoquais2002">παγ(άρχου)</rdg> 
                <rdg resp="#feisselBE">παγ(ανῶν)</rdg></app></listApp></div>
           
            
                <div type="translation" xml:lang="fr" source="#ityr2006"><p>Emplacement du 'pagarque' des Bleus</p>
           </div>
           <div type="translation" xml:lang="en" resp="#cmr"><p>Place of Blue pagani?</p>
           </div>
                
         
            <div type="commentary">
                <p>Feissel sees a reference to <foreign xml:lang="la">Pag(ani)</foreign> here and in <ref type="inscription" n="Factions060">text 60</ref>; he points to 
                    the use of <foreign xml:lang="la">paganus</foreign> for 'ordinary members", citing  <ref target="https://papyri.info/ddbdp/p.oxy;54;3758">P.Oxy 54.3758</ref>, where one group of those liable for payment are called 
                    παγανοί; less clear is what it means in a list by professions <ref target="https://papyri.info/ddbdp/bgu;1;344">BGU 1,344</ref>. A couple of funerary inscriptions 
                    for pagani with no further explanation, are probably for local ?non-urban people
                    <ref target="https://edh.ub.uni-heidelberg.de/edh/inschrift/HD012630">https://edh.ub.uni-heidelberg.de/edh/inschrift/HD012630</ref>, 
                    <ref target="https://edh.ub.uni-heidelberg.de/edh/inschrift/HD043121">https://edh.ub.uni-heidelberg.de/edh/inschrift/HD043121</ref>. But <foreign xml:lang="la">paganus</foreign> 
                    is also used to describe gladiators in at least two funerary texts: 
                    Robert, <ref target="https://zenon.dainst.org/Record/000209739">Gladiateurs</ref> 20, at Edessa (available at <ref target="https://epigraphy.packhum.org/text/150969">PHI</ref><!-- check new edition 2015, now no.261, with a bibliography -->) and at Salona, 
                    the funerary urn of a gladiator, <ref target="https://edh.ub.uni-heidelberg.de/edh/inschrift/HD027274">https://edh.ub.uni-heidelberg.de/edh/inschrift/HD027274</ref>.
                    The term is found at Rome in the catalogue of a familia of gladiators (CIL VI, 631, Dessau 5084, whence EDCS 17300774), 
                    under Commodus, where the third decurio lists 2 members as pagani.   
                    
                </p>
                
            </div>
            
